<h2 id="introduction">Introduction</h2>

<p>The problem comes from a stochastic PDE:</p>

\[\dfrac{du}{dt}=\Delta u-Eu^2+\xi\]

<p>Where ¬† $u$ ¬† is a function of $t$ and $x$, $x\in$ [0,1], and ¬† $\xi$ ¬† is space-time white noise.</p>

<p>We want to understand invariant measure of the stochastic PDE.</p>

<p>However, since it‚Äôs complicated to deal with SPDE, we can try to make a finite difference approximation. Let‚Äôs take n points from [0,1].</p>

<p>Then it becomes an SDE system:</p>

\[dX_t^i=(X_t^{i-1}+X_t^{i+1}-2X_t^{i}-{EX_t^i}^2\cdot X_t^i)dt+dB_t^i\]

<p>where $i=1,‚Ä¶,n$. We take a periodic boundary condition here, namely $X_t^0=X_t^n$ and $X_t^{n+1}=X_t^1$.</p>

<p>We want to figure out the invariant measure of this SDE system.</p>

<h2 id="preliminary">Preliminary</h2>

<h3 id="fokkerplanck-equation">Fokker‚ÄìPlanck equation</h3>

<p>The Fokker‚ÄìPlanck equation is a partial differential equation that describes the time evolution of the probability density function of the random variebles. For a general case, if</p>

\[dX_t=\mu (X_t, t)dt+\sigma (X_t, t) dB_t\]

<p>where $X_t$ and $\mu(X_t,t)$ are n-dimensional random vectors, $\sigma (X_t,t)$ is an n$\times$m matrix and $B_t$ is an m-dimensional standard Wiener process, the probability density $p(x,t)$ for $X_t$ satisfies the Fokker‚ÄìPlanck-equation:</p>

\[\frac{\partial p(\mathbf{x}, t)}{\partial t}=-\sum\limits_{i=1}^{N} \frac{\partial}{\partial x_{i}}\left[\mu_{i}(\mathbf{x}, t) p(\mathbf{x}, t)\right]+\sum_{i=1}^{N} \sum_{j=1}^{N} \frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x_{i} \partial x_{j}}\left[D_{i j}(\mathbf{x}, t) p(\mathbf{x}, t)\right]\]

<p>with drift vector $\mu = (\mu_1,‚Ä¶,\mu_N)$ and diffusion tensor $D = \frac{1}{2}\sigma \sigma^T$, i.e.</p>

\[D_{i j}(\mathbf{x}, t)=\frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=1}^{M} \sigma_{i k}(\mathbf{x}, t) \sigma_{j k}(\mathbf{x}, t)\]

<p>For our problem, which is</p>

<p>$\begin{pmatrix} X_t^1 \ X_t^2 \ \vdot \ X_t^n \end{pmatrix}$</p>

